WEBVTT

01:32.827 --> 01:36.428
[STATION MASTER BLOWING WHISTLE]

01:38.399 --> 01:43.268
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING]

01:48.642 --> 01:52.444
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATION]

02:07.428 --> 02:10.896
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATION]

02:43.697 --> 02:48.534
[WOMEN SCREAMING]

03:02.283 --> 03:06.618
[BABY CRYING]

03:22.703 --> 03:23.902
[DOG BARKING]

03:50.598 --> 03:56.335
[PEOPLE SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

03:59.473 --> 04:02.507
Please. Please. Please!

04:02.509 --> 04:03.575
Open.

04:05.279 --> 04:06.745
Please.

04:08.983 --> 04:12.017
-Please.
-The door. The door.

04:13.420 --> 04:14.720
Remember Grandmere's house.

04:14.722 --> 04:16.521
Please, Papa, no.

04:16.523 --> 04:19.625
Papa, I don't want to go.

04:19.627 --> 04:22.427
Please, Papa, no. [SOBBING]

04:23.330 --> 04:24.496
Papa!

05:39.073 --> 05:43.809
OLD JO:<i> Growing up</i>
<i> is different for everyone.</i>

05:43.811 --> 05:47.679
<i> For the lucky few,</i>
<i> time does all the work.</i>

05:47.681 --> 05:50.582
<i>Others are not given a choice.</i>

05:50.584 --> 05:52.417
<i> This is my story.</i>

05:52.419 --> 05:55.721
<i> The story of when war</i>
<i> came to my village,</i>

05:55.723 --> 05:57.689
<i> my valley, my world.</i>

05:57.691 --> 06:01.393
<i> Of how I became a man.</i>

06:05.432 --> 06:10.869
<i> Papa always used to tell me,</i>
<i> "Never fall asleep, Jo.</i>

06:10.871 --> 06:12.504
<i> "Whittle a stick,</i>

06:12.506 --> 06:16.007
<i> "pick berries,</i>
<i> read your comic if you must,</i>

06:16.009 --> 06:20.045
<i> "but don't close your eyes.</i>
<i> Not for one second."</i>

06:22.416 --> 06:24.649
[BIRD CALLING]

06:34.728 --> 06:38.797
<i>But Papa had not woken at dawn</i>
<i> to milk the sheep,</i>

06:38.799 --> 06:42.134
<i> and anyway,</i>
<i> reading is tiring work,</i>

06:42.136 --> 06:45.971
<i> even if I only ever looked</i>
<i> at the pictures.</i>

06:47.775 --> 06:54.012
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

07:08.061 --> 07:12.164
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

07:12.166 --> 07:13.932
[BARKING]

07:14.902 --> 07:16.168
Oh.

07:16.170 --> 07:17.436
What is it?

07:17.438 --> 07:18.970
[BARKING CONTINUES]

07:22.609 --> 07:27.112
[BEAR GROWLING]

07:52.639 --> 07:53.705
No!

07:54.174 --> 07:55.240
[DOG WHIMPERS]

07:59.580 --> 08:01.947
Bear! Bear!
There's a bear in the woods!

08:04.151 --> 08:05.217
Are you all right, Jo?

08:05.219 --> 08:06.685
-Out of my way!
-Are you hurt?

08:06.687 --> 08:08.720
Rouf, Maman.
He's still up there!

08:08.722 --> 08:10.889
The sheep, Jo.
What about the sheep?

08:10.891 --> 08:12.824
I don't know, Grandpere.

08:12.826 --> 08:14.226
I ran away.

08:22.236 --> 08:25.904
Jo? Jo. You're too young to go.

08:25.906 --> 08:28.106
Come and help me
in the kitchen, please.

08:31.578 --> 08:33.745
[MEN TALKING INDISTINCTLY]

08:33.747 --> 08:36.548
[GREETING EACH OTHER]

08:52.699 --> 08:54.132
Think it's ready.

08:59.873 --> 09:01.273
Beautiful.

09:01.275 --> 09:02.941
Yes.

09:02.943 --> 09:04.643
You can go.

09:09.816 --> 09:12.817
[GUNSHOTS IN THE DISTANCE]

09:16.590 --> 09:18.757
[GUNSHOTS CONTINUE]

09:20.827 --> 09:23.128
[CROWD MURMURING]

09:28.902 --> 09:30.201
<i> Souriez!</i>

09:36.176 --> 09:37.943
Grandpere, where's Rouf?

09:40.881 --> 09:42.180
Did you find him?

09:46.119 --> 09:48.753
-[LITTLE BOY GROWLING]
-[MAN CHUCKLES]

09:48.755 --> 09:50.922
My son thinks he is a bear.

09:53.994 --> 09:56.795
Settle down now, everyone.
That includes you, Hubert.

09:56.797 --> 10:01.766
I just want to thank Jo Lalande
for what he did today.

10:01.768 --> 10:04.803
Without him, there'd be no bear.

10:04.805 --> 10:08.673
Who knows what damage it might
have caused to our flocks?

10:08.675 --> 10:10.875
Especially one so low down
from the mountain.

10:10.877 --> 10:12.243
So,

10:12.245 --> 10:15.981
here's to Jo.
Here's to the bear.

10:15.983 --> 10:17.782
And down with the Boche.

10:17.784 --> 10:19.951
ALL: Down with the Boche.

10:19.953 --> 10:21.953
-Long live the bear.
-Long live the bear.

10:28.061 --> 10:29.661
Rouf!

10:32.032 --> 10:33.732
Rouf!

10:48.949 --> 10:50.882
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

11:01.028 --> 11:02.093
Rouf!

11:03.697 --> 11:04.763
Rouf!

11:05.832 --> 11:07.999
[WHIMPERING]

11:08.001 --> 11:10.068
I thought I'd lost you.

11:11.972 --> 11:14.773
So, you came back for your dog.

11:16.710 --> 11:18.843
Very brave of you

11:18.845 --> 11:20.745
after all the shooting
that went on.

11:22.883 --> 11:24.115
The bleeding's stopped now.

11:24.985 --> 11:26.451
Here boy, come on, Rouf.

11:26.453 --> 11:28.186
-Let's go.
-Keep your voice down.

11:28.188 --> 11:30.722
I don't want you frightening
any more bears today.

11:36.263 --> 11:38.396
I saw the whole thing, you know.

11:38.398 --> 11:41.833
The bear, the sheep scattering,

11:41.835 --> 11:43.802
you scattering.

11:51.445 --> 11:53.478
Relax, it's just bread.

11:56.183 --> 11:57.782
What's your name, boy?

11:59.052 --> 12:00.118
Jo Lalande.

12:01.755 --> 12:03.455
Nice yo meet you, Jo Lalande.

12:05.392 --> 12:06.791
She could have
got away, you know.

12:06.793 --> 12:09.027
-Who?
-The bear.

12:09.028 --> 12:11.262
Mother bear. She was
leading them away from her cub.

12:18.939 --> 12:21.473
He'll smell
the milk soon enough.

12:21.475 --> 12:24.943
He won't be able to resist.

12:24.945 --> 12:27.979
Right away down the valley
she took them as well,

12:27.981 --> 12:30.215
all for this little guy.

12:30.217 --> 12:32.417
He'll die out here
without his mother, won't he?

12:32.419 --> 12:34.352
You're right about that, Jo.

12:34.354 --> 12:36.387
Which is why
he's coming home
with one of us.

12:37.791 --> 12:38.857
What's your name?

12:38.859 --> 12:40.458
What do you want with my name?

12:40.460 --> 12:42.093
I told you mine.

12:44.030 --> 12:45.764
I'll just ask
in the village about you.

12:45.766 --> 12:47.065
You won't do that.

12:47.067 --> 12:49.484
Why not?

12:49.485 --> 12:51.902
Because I'll make sure
the whole village knows
about your little nap.

12:51.905 --> 12:54.339
I told you. I saw it all.

12:54.341 --> 12:56.441
So let's just keep this
a secret, huh?

12:57.844 --> 13:00.979
A secret between you and me.

13:01.982 --> 13:05.950
Agreed? We better get going.

13:05.952 --> 13:08.787
[BEAR CUB GURGLES]

13:08.789 --> 13:11.856
And don't be
too hard on yourself
about what happened today.

13:13.527 --> 13:17.562
You had your job to do,
and the mother bear,
she had hers.

13:18.398 --> 13:20.431
And besides,

13:22.102 --> 13:23.835
if none of it
had happened,

13:23.837 --> 13:25.436
we never would have met.

13:25.438 --> 13:27.906
-We haven't met.
-[CHUCKLES]

13:29.843 --> 13:31.309
No, we haven't.

13:32.445 --> 13:33.545
So long.

13:44.257 --> 13:46.558
[ROUF WHIMPERS]

14:31.504 --> 14:33.271
ALICE: You're a fool.

14:33.273 --> 14:34.906
BENJAMIN: Alice...

14:34.908 --> 14:37.108
ALICE: You promised me
you'll only go out at night.

14:37.110 --> 14:39.227
You gave me your word.

14:39.228 --> 14:41.345
The boy doesn't know
who I am, what I am,
or where are we from.

14:41.348 --> 14:42.914
-We'll be fine.
-No.

14:42.916 --> 14:45.884
We won't be fine.
Everything won't be fine.

14:45.886 --> 14:48.119
What happens when he goes home
and tells everybody

14:48.121 --> 14:50.388
about the stranger
he met in the woods?

14:50.390 --> 14:53.591
They may be simple country folk
but they are not stupid.

14:53.593 --> 14:55.526
You can't keep me
locked in here forever.

14:55.528 --> 14:58.129
I never wanted you here
in the first place.

14:59.566 --> 15:03.134
I don't doubt that to be true.
But Florence did.

15:03.136 --> 15:04.402
She would want me here.

15:04.404 --> 15:05.470
[PIGS GRUNTING]

15:05.472 --> 15:07.939
Yes, she would.

15:07.940 --> 15:10.407
And if she was here,
maybe she'd knock
some sense into you.

15:13.246 --> 15:16.614
Alice, the boy won't
say anything.

15:16.616 --> 15:18.416
I've shamed him
into secrecy.

15:19.653 --> 15:21.352
You're all
I have left, Benjamin.

15:22.322 --> 15:24.522
And Anya.

15:24.524 --> 15:27.158
For all we know, she could
walk through that door
at any second.

15:30.563 --> 15:33.665
Until then,
we wait and pray.

15:36.970 --> 15:39.003
I better go see to the pigs.

15:44.544 --> 15:46.010
Rouf, come on, let's go.

15:54.955 --> 15:59.023
MAN ON RADIO:<i> In</i>
<i> the occupied part of France,</i>
<i> the German Reich</i>

15:59.025 --> 16:02.627
<i>has been exercising all rights</i>
<i> of an occupying power,</i>

16:02.629 --> 16:05.663
<i> and the French Government</i>
<i> has governed zonally</i>

16:05.665 --> 16:09.334
<i> and committed itself</i>
<i> to facilitate by all means</i>

16:09.336 --> 16:13.171
<i> the regulations pertaining to</i>
<i>the rights of the German Reich</i>

16:13.173 --> 16:15.740
<i> and to putting them in place</i>

16:15.742 --> 16:19.010
<i> with the cooperation</i>
<i> of the French administration.</i>

16:19.012 --> 16:21.412
-Monsieur, the Germans are here.
<i> -The French government</i>

16:21.414 --> 16:24.015
<i> was invited to continue</i>
<i> with all authority</i>

16:24.017 --> 16:27.552
<i> -and administrative services</i>
<i> in the occupied territory...</i>
-[GIGGLES]

16:27.554 --> 16:29.754
Out of here! Out!

16:29.756 --> 16:32.323
<i> ...regulation of the German</i>
<i> military's authority,</i>

16:32.325 --> 16:34.492
That's just what they said.
The Germans are here.

16:34.494 --> 16:42.233
TEACHER: T-O-R-P-E-U-R.

16:42.235 --> 16:46.237
<i> Torpeur.</i> Not hibernation,
as many people think.

16:47.507 --> 16:52.543
Bears need to wake
to feed and protect their cubs.

16:52.545 --> 16:56.547
A<i> torpeur</i> is more of
a deep sleep.

16:56.549 --> 16:59.751
Much like many of you
seem to be in,
each and every morning.

16:59.753 --> 17:01.052
[ALL GIGGLE]

17:04.758 --> 17:07.325
Do they eat people, Miss?

17:07.327 --> 17:09.594
Not unless
they're really hungry.

17:10.730 --> 17:11.796
Psst.

17:12.499 --> 17:13.698
They drink milk.

17:29.516 --> 17:31.582
-Who was that lady...
-You stay well away
from that woman.

17:31.584 --> 17:33.317
You hear me?

17:33.319 --> 17:36.320
No matter what Grandpere
has to say about her.

17:36.322 --> 17:37.555
Why don't you
like here, Maman?

17:37.557 --> 17:40.224
Because she doesn't like us.

17:40.226 --> 17:43.227
And she's caused
enough upset in this village
to last a lifetime.

18:13.093 --> 18:14.759
I'm off to see Hubert.

18:14.761 --> 18:18.096
Back before it
gets dark.
You hear me?

18:18.631 --> 18:19.697
Jo!

19:34.574 --> 19:35.640
That's mine.

19:39.779 --> 19:41.913
We need to talk,
Joseph Lalande.

19:44.884 --> 19:47.218
Eat up, boy.

19:47.219 --> 19:49.553
Otherwise,
I feed it to the pigs.
They're hungry, you know.

19:53.193 --> 19:54.258
So tell me, boy,

19:55.495 --> 19:57.361
what did you see
in the barn?

19:58.431 --> 19:59.730
Nothing, Madame.

19:59.732 --> 20:00.798
Nothing?

20:01.768 --> 20:04.686
I know your father.

20:04.687 --> 20:07.605
He's a hard-working shepherd
when he's not away soldiering.

20:07.607 --> 20:11.709
Takes after his father,
your grandfather.

20:11.711 --> 20:14.478
But maybe the less said
about him, the better.

20:15.982 --> 20:18.950
I'll ask you
one more time, boy.

20:18.952 --> 20:21.352
What did you see
in the barn?

20:21.354 --> 20:24.555
I... I was only looking
for the bear cub.

20:24.557 --> 20:26.557
You're not
answering the question.

20:26.559 --> 20:27.658
No.

20:28.695 --> 20:30.428
You always
tell the truth?

20:33.399 --> 20:36.334
No, Madame.

20:36.336 --> 20:39.670
It's a rare thing,
an honest boy.

20:39.672 --> 20:43.641
You know, people tend to
pick and choose with honesty.

20:43.643 --> 20:45.610
It doesn't mean
you can trust them.

20:45.612 --> 20:48.312
I've known about him for...
for weeks

20:48.314 --> 20:49.580
and I haven't told anyone.

20:49.582 --> 20:51.649
What's to stop you
telling them now?

20:51.651 --> 20:53.751
I just wouldn't.
I promise.

21:00.493 --> 21:03.628
I'm a Jew.
You know what that is?

21:03.630 --> 21:04.929
Aren't they in the Bible?

21:06.733 --> 21:08.666
Yes, we're in the Bible.

21:08.668 --> 21:11.569
But plenty of people
think that's where we
should have stayed.

21:14.007 --> 21:16.040
Do you know what the Germans
do to the Jews?

21:19.579 --> 21:22.380
The Germans forced us
to flee our homes
and move to Paris.

21:24.417 --> 21:25.583
I thought we were safe.

21:26.853 --> 21:28.586
<i> My little Anya and I.</i>

21:31.491 --> 21:32.723
I was wrong.

21:32.725 --> 21:34.458
Papa.

21:48.941 --> 21:51.008
We always said,
if we ever got separated,

21:51.010 --> 21:53.377
we would meet
at Grandmere's house.

21:53.913 --> 21:55.646
I'm here.

21:55.648 --> 21:57.481
And I'm staying
till Anya comes.

21:58.384 --> 22:00.318
So, the little girl?

22:00.320 --> 22:03.054
The girl in the barn is Leah.
There are four more
on the way.

22:03.656 --> 22:05.723
Four more what?

22:05.725 --> 22:08.526
Children.
Jewish children.

22:09.595 --> 22:12.730
Some people collect
coins, stamps.

22:13.933 --> 22:16.767
We collect enemies
of the Reich.

22:16.769 --> 22:19.503
They get passed down
through France.

22:19.505 --> 22:23.674
And when they get here,
Benjamin gets them out
from under my feet,

22:23.676 --> 22:26.777
by smuggling them
across the mountains
into Spain.

22:27.480 --> 22:29.547
They're safe there.

22:29.548 --> 22:31.615
But if Leah can
make it here from Warsaw,
then so can Anya.

22:32.585 --> 22:34.452
That's why I'll never
give up hope.

22:35.555 --> 22:37.621
One day, Anya will be
one of those children.

22:37.623 --> 22:39.957
And until that day,
may God protect her

22:39.959 --> 22:41.592
-in Jesus' name. Amen.
-LEAH:<i> Bonjour.</i>

22:43.096 --> 22:44.995
Leah. Leah.

22:44.997 --> 22:46.564
ALICE: Benjamin.

22:47.734 --> 22:49.033
Let me help you.

22:49.669 --> 22:50.835
[SIGHS]

22:52.905 --> 22:55.406
Don't worry, Alice.

22:55.408 --> 22:56.907
She'll stay put
when then others come.

22:56.909 --> 22:58.976
You better make sure
that she does.

22:58.978 --> 23:00.811
And you.

23:00.813 --> 23:02.947
I was thinking of
swearing you to secrecy.

23:02.949 --> 23:04.815
A blood oath
if necessary.

23:04.817 --> 23:06.751
No. No, Madame.

23:06.753 --> 23:09.120
Then go. And boy,

23:09.122 --> 23:11.389
don't you even dream
of coming back here.

23:18.164 --> 23:20.965
So what's happened
to the bear cub?

23:20.967 --> 23:23.801
I left him
in the mountains
a week ago.

23:23.803 --> 23:26.570
He was big enough
to fend for himself.

23:26.572 --> 23:28.072
I haven't seen him since.

23:30.543 --> 23:33.411
OLD JO:<i> My mind was racing</i>
<i> all the way home.</i>

23:33.413 --> 23:34.879
<i> I thought about</i>
<i> the bear cub</i>

23:34.881 --> 23:37.047
<i> and whether he</i>
<i> missed his mother,</i>

23:37.049 --> 23:40.184
<i> about Anya and where</i>
<i> she might be.</i>

23:40.186 --> 23:44.054
<i>And then, there was the mystery</i>
<i> of the vehicles,</i>

23:44.056 --> 23:47.158
<i> winding their way</i>
<i> up the mountain</i>
<i> to our village.</i>

23:47.827 --> 23:52.830
[CONVERSING IN GERMAN]

23:59.439 --> 24:03.474
OLD JO:<i> I had never</i>
<i> seen German writing before.</i>

24:03.476 --> 24:06.477
<i> My reading in French</i>
<i> wasn't much better,</i>

24:06.479 --> 24:09.180
<i> but I could make out</i>
<i> the names of three people</i>

24:09.182 --> 24:11.182
<i> from the neighboring village.</i>

24:11.184 --> 24:15.553
<i> Pierre, Mari, Batiste,</i>
<i> and then</i>

24:15.555 --> 24:18.889
<i> I read the word "executed."</i>

24:20.526 --> 24:22.793
-[CROWD MURMURING]
-SOLDIER: Quiet please.

24:22.795 --> 24:24.962
Everyone, quiet.

24:25.965 --> 24:28.732
As many of you
are already aware,

24:28.734 --> 24:31.001
under the orders of
the Vichy government,

24:31.003 --> 24:35.673
three enemies of the Reich
were executed in Bedous.

24:35.675 --> 24:38.175
Me and my men have been
posted here in Lescun

24:38.177 --> 24:41.812
to make sure that
nothing of the like
occurs in this village.

24:41.814 --> 24:45.950
From tonight, a 9:30 curfew
will be strictly enforced,

24:45.952 --> 24:48.018
papers must be carried
at all times,

24:48.020 --> 24:51.522
and around-the-clock
patrols will take place
around the border

24:51.524 --> 24:55.059
to make sure that
no feeling Frenchman
or Jew

24:55.061 --> 24:58.062
crosses those mountains
into Spain.

24:58.064 --> 25:01.065
The parish will provide
our garrison headquarters,

25:01.067 --> 25:03.667
and for any of you
with information,

25:03.669 --> 25:05.536
our door is always open.

25:05.538 --> 25:07.538
-[HUBERT IMITATING GUNFIRE]
-For those with secrets,

25:07.540 --> 25:09.006
rest assured,

25:09.008 --> 25:11.609
we will come to your door.

25:11.611 --> 25:13.210
If we find anyone in Lescun

25:13.212 --> 25:15.546
aiding the enemies
of the Reich,

25:15.548 --> 25:18.883
they will face the same fate
as the traitors in Bedous.

25:18.885 --> 25:23.687
-[IMITATING GUNFIRE]
-[GIGGLING]

25:23.689 --> 25:26.891
[GRUNTING]

25:26.893 --> 25:29.560
Hubert! Hubert!

25:29.562 --> 25:31.562
No, no, no.
Please. Please.

25:31.564 --> 25:34.532
My son, it's a little joke.
He won't hurt you.

25:34.534 --> 25:36.967
If he's so harmless,
let him go.

25:40.072 --> 25:41.872
No. No, no.

25:44.076 --> 25:47.111
[IMITATING GUNFIRE]

25:47.113 --> 25:49.713
SARTHOL: No, please. No, please.

25:49.715 --> 25:51.749
SOLDIER: Boom!

25:51.751 --> 25:54.118
[CHUCKLES]

25:54.120 --> 25:55.252
You're right.

25:55.988 --> 25:58.322
He's a funny one, hmm?

26:00.826 --> 26:02.660
9:30 curfew.

26:02.662 --> 26:05.563
We have a job to do,
and we will do it.

26:06.832 --> 26:07.965
<i> Ja?</i>

26:12.605 --> 26:15.105
MAMAN: He could have
got himself killed,
your friend Hubert.

26:15.107 --> 26:18.242
You don't do that
with the Germans,
it's not a game.

26:18.244 --> 26:20.077
Are you listening, Jo?

26:20.079 --> 26:22.212
I said, he could have
got himself killed.

26:22.214 --> 26:25.716
He only did
what the rest of us
wanted to.

26:26.819 --> 26:29.053
What good
would that do?

26:29.055 --> 26:30.721
We don't need another martyr.

26:30.723 --> 26:33.123
There's too many names
of good young men

26:33.125 --> 26:34.792
on that monument already.

26:34.794 --> 26:38.195
And now there will be
three more from Bedous.

26:38.197 --> 26:41.332
There's always a price
to be paid.

26:41.334 --> 26:43.267
How can you say that?

26:43.269 --> 26:46.170
This village has paid
enough of a price already.

26:46.172 --> 26:49.273
And this house
is still paying,
and for what?

26:49.275 --> 26:51.909
You may have a death wish,
Henri, but I don't.

26:51.911 --> 26:53.711
CHRISTINE: Maman, I can't sleep.

26:53.713 --> 26:55.012
[SIGHS] Give me
strength, please.

26:55.014 --> 26:56.914
Jo, put her back
to bed for me.

26:56.916 --> 27:00.351
CHRISTINE: Maman. [WHINES]

27:00.353 --> 27:02.653
JO: Come on Christine,
back to bed.

27:02.655 --> 27:07.625
[CHRISTINE WHINES]

27:31.417 --> 27:35.085
He'll be back, Lise.
I promise.

27:36.389 --> 27:38.389
Don't make promises
you can't keep.

27:40.359 --> 27:43.360
[PIGS GRUNTING]

27:51.337 --> 27:54.304
Madame! Madame!

27:55.241 --> 27:57.141
Did I not make
myself clear?

27:57.143 --> 27:58.442
I had to come,
I had to tell you.

27:58.444 --> 28:00.878
German soldiers.
They're in the village.

28:00.880 --> 28:02.846
And they've got patrols
up in the mountains.

28:04.383 --> 28:05.949
Where's Benjamin?

28:05.951 --> 28:08.118
He left last night
with Leah.

28:10.289 --> 28:12.289
Which crossing
does he take?

28:12.291 --> 28:13.824
[SIGHS] Which crossing?

28:13.826 --> 28:16.326
He takes the Col de Laraille.

28:16.328 --> 28:19.296
God bless you!
God bless you, boy.

28:28.174 --> 28:30.040
[GERMAN SOLDIERS TALKING
IN THE DISTANCE]

28:55.000 --> 28:58.802
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

29:11.484 --> 29:13.083
Benjamin!

29:17.757 --> 29:19.823
Benjamin!

29:20.226 --> 29:22.159
Benjamin!

29:26.398 --> 29:28.899
BENJAMIN: Stop shouting.

29:28.901 --> 29:30.367
JO: Benjamin?

29:32.004 --> 29:33.904
BENJAMIN: Keep your voice down.

29:40.479 --> 29:42.446
[LEAH WHIMPERING]

29:57.963 --> 29:59.830
Am I ever going to
get rid of you?

29:59.832 --> 30:02.099
What happened?

30:02.100 --> 30:04.367
Soldiers everywhere.
I had to carry Leah.

30:05.838 --> 30:07.137
I turned it.

30:11.510 --> 30:13.510
We have to
get you down.

30:13.512 --> 30:15.312
But what about
the soldiers?

30:15.314 --> 30:17.298
I saw them leaving.

30:17.299 --> 30:19.283
They'll know no one
can make it across
the mountains in this.

30:19.285 --> 30:22.920
Then take Leah down.
You can't take us both.

30:22.922 --> 30:26.056
And I can't lose her.
I won't.

30:27.092 --> 30:28.258
Not again.

30:33.499 --> 30:35.132
JO: You can make it.

30:37.603 --> 30:40.971
[BENJAMIN GRUNTING]

30:58.624 --> 31:05.863
[BENJAMIN AND JO
SINGING A FRENCH SONG]

31:10.135 --> 31:11.602
You saved us.

31:11.604 --> 31:13.904
Oh, Jo. Thank you.

31:19.645 --> 31:21.445
There you are,<i> ma chere.</i>

31:23.082 --> 31:28.919
[HUBERT HUMMING SOFTLY]

31:32.892 --> 31:35.325
AUDAP: How are you
getting on there, Amelie?

31:35.327 --> 31:37.060
Okay, remember everyone,

31:37.062 --> 31:40.631
plants are like human beings.

31:40.633 --> 31:45.435
They release acid carbonate...

31:46.639 --> 31:48.038
[SHIVERING]

31:51.410 --> 31:52.542
[COUGHING]

31:52.544 --> 31:55.112
AUDAP: Do you
have any questions?

32:03.222 --> 32:05.239
No one?

32:05.240 --> 32:07.257
I assume that means
you've done a very good job.

32:07.259 --> 32:09.993
I'm very impressed.
This is great work.

32:09.995 --> 32:12.262
Your handwriting
has improved a lot.

32:13.432 --> 32:16.967
SOLDIER:<i> Name, bitte.</i>
This is your only rifle?

32:19.605 --> 32:23.006
As if they haven't
humiliated us enough.

32:26.045 --> 32:27.978
SOLDIER:<i> Guten tag,</i> Hubert.

32:28.948 --> 32:30.180
The last thing we want

32:30.182 --> 32:32.683
is to make them
feel at home.

32:32.685 --> 32:35.686
They're invaders.
Never forget that.

32:37.423 --> 32:39.323
And if it is rifles they want,

32:39.325 --> 32:42.526
then rifles is what they'll get.

32:45.431 --> 32:46.596
Grab this.

33:07.386 --> 33:10.020
This is so when
the time comes...

33:10.022 --> 33:14.291
If the time comes
at least I'll be taking
one of them with me.

33:18.731 --> 33:21.098
Give us a hand. Push.

33:23.602 --> 33:25.469
[GRUNTS]

33:28.474 --> 33:30.507
Go to
the other side.

33:35.180 --> 33:36.380
[GRUNTS]

33:40.619 --> 33:43.286
Hubert, give me that.

33:43.288 --> 33:45.055
Give me the old one.

33:58.037 --> 34:02.272
Killed a few of
your lot with this in
the Battle of Verdun.

34:03.642 --> 34:05.509
Make sure to oil it.

34:14.453 --> 34:17.220
Verdun, did you just say?

34:17.222 --> 34:18.488
That's right.

34:19.291 --> 34:20.490
Verdun.

34:30.202 --> 34:32.235
Might have been
shooting that at me, then.

34:34.206 --> 34:36.740
You weren't at Verdun.

34:36.742 --> 34:38.275
You would have only
been a child.

34:39.278 --> 34:40.644
Sixteen.

34:41.713 --> 34:44.181
But not for long.

34:52.257 --> 34:53.723
HENRI:<i> Alice.</i>

34:53.725 --> 34:55.325
Alice.

34:57.863 --> 34:59.863
You're looking
younger than ever.

34:59.865 --> 35:01.398
[ALICE CHUCKLES]

35:01.400 --> 35:02.799
You old goat.

35:03.869 --> 35:05.168
Allow me.

35:05.737 --> 35:06.837
Yes.

35:08.207 --> 35:09.773
Take this.

35:11.844 --> 35:14.344
You're looking very pleased
with yourself.

35:14.346 --> 35:16.480
I have just come
to the realization

35:16.482 --> 35:19.382
that my genius
knows no bounds.

35:19.384 --> 35:21.852
[CHUCKLES] And what
brought you to
that conclusion?

35:21.854 --> 35:25.388
This is our little secret.
Isn't it, boys?

35:25.390 --> 35:27.791
We're all allowed
our little secrets.

35:27.793 --> 35:29.826
-[CHUCKLES]
-<i> Guten tag,</i> Hubert.

35:30.562 --> 35:34.364
[MUMBLES]

35:35.434 --> 35:37.367
-Uh-huh.
-Can he manage that?

35:37.369 --> 35:39.569
Strong boy he is.

35:39.571 --> 35:42.272
From good stock
as well, you know.

35:42.274 --> 35:43.507
Lend him to me.

35:43.509 --> 35:44.641
HENRI: What for?

35:44.643 --> 35:46.960
ALICE: He can
do my shopping.

35:46.961 --> 35:49.278
I don't know, Alice.
With his father being
away and all that...

35:49.281 --> 35:50.714
I've got the sheep.

35:50.716 --> 35:53.283
I'll be doing
the transhumance this year.

35:53.285 --> 35:56.786
You're too young to be
up the mountains all summer
with the sheep, Jo.

35:57.523 --> 35:59.189
ALICE: I'd pay him.

35:59.191 --> 36:01.892
Half a kilo of honey
a week.

36:03.428 --> 36:05.162
When do you
want him to start?

36:05.164 --> 36:06.363
Now.

36:07.432 --> 36:10.333
Come along, boy.
I won't bite.

36:17.943 --> 36:20.677
My mom never gets
this much food
with her ration tickets.

36:20.679 --> 36:21.878
[CHUCKLES]

36:21.880 --> 36:23.847
Madame Jollet is
quite the capitalist.

36:23.849 --> 36:26.483
She'll make allowances
as long as you can pay.

36:27.719 --> 36:30.287
Is it enough for Leah
and the others?

36:30.289 --> 36:32.423
Barely.

36:32.424 --> 36:34.558
And we have three more children
arriving any day now.

36:39.631 --> 36:41.198
When can Benjamin take them?

36:41.200 --> 36:43.600
He can't. Not for months
with that ankle.

36:43.602 --> 36:46.570
And even then,
they'll never get them
past the patrol.

36:48.340 --> 36:49.873
We can't take these children

36:49.875 --> 36:51.942
back to where
they come from,

36:53.445 --> 36:55.579
and we can't take them
where they need to go.

36:56.982 --> 36:59.749
I'm sorry, Jo.
You're the only one I can ask.

37:05.257 --> 37:08.692
OLD JO:<i> Each week, the widow's</i>
<i> shopping list got longer</i>

37:08.694 --> 37:10.961
<i> and the bags got heavier.</i>

37:10.963 --> 37:13.263
<i> I was not allowed</i>
<i> to see the children,</i>

37:13.265 --> 37:16.700
<i> but I knew their numbers</i>
<i> were growing.</i>

37:16.702 --> 37:19.302
<i> With the Germans</i>
<i> patrolling the mountains,</i>

37:19.304 --> 37:22.906
<i> there was no way</i>
<i> of getting them</i>
<i> across to Spain.</i>

37:24.443 --> 37:27.377
<i> And then, the winter came.</i>

37:27.379 --> 37:30.780
<i> Everyone in the valley</i>
<i> knew it was too dangerous</i>

37:30.782 --> 37:32.916
<i> to try and cross in winter.</i>

37:32.918 --> 37:37.787
<i> But the Germans continued</i>
<i> their patrols nonetheless,</i>

37:37.789 --> 37:39.623
<i> whatever the weather...</i>

37:40.392 --> 37:41.725
<i> Much like me.</i>

37:41.727 --> 37:43.460
<i> I would make the journey</i>

37:43.462 --> 37:46.496
<i> to Widow Horcada's</i>
<i> every week,</i>

37:46.498 --> 37:48.865
<i> come rain, come shine.</i>

37:59.278 --> 38:01.945
-BOY: Hey!
-[LAUGHS]

38:01.947 --> 38:03.880
[MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO]

38:05.717 --> 38:08.018
How many times?
Give me the shopping list.

38:17.729 --> 38:19.429
Tell her it'll be double
next week.

38:23.502 --> 38:25.635
And you keep your hands
to yourself.

38:40.752 --> 38:41.951
Good morning.

38:45.924 --> 38:46.489
<i> Bonjour.</i>

38:50.896 --> 38:53.530
Corporal Hoffman. Cigarettes?

38:53.532 --> 38:54.898
The boy was here first.

38:54.900 --> 38:56.399
But Corporal...

38:56.401 --> 38:57.567
I insist.

39:01.840 --> 39:03.406
You have a large family?

39:03.408 --> 39:05.508
It's for Widow Horcada,
Corporal.

39:05.510 --> 39:06.943
Jo here does her shopping.

39:07.746 --> 39:09.913
Widow Horcada.

39:09.915 --> 39:12.449
I do like a woman
with a big appetite.

39:12.451 --> 39:14.050
I can't believe it myself.

39:14.052 --> 39:16.386
Maybe she has some guests
we don't know about.

39:16.388 --> 39:18.855
Please, monsieur.
You're only buying cigarettes.

39:18.857 --> 39:20.857
I'll wait.

39:20.859 --> 39:23.993
Tell me, madame.
The rations, have they gone up?

39:23.995 --> 39:26.496
I expect you know
better than me, Corporal.

39:26.498 --> 39:30.600
I only know that trading
on the black market is illegal.

39:30.602 --> 39:32.569
But this is not
the black market.

39:35.540 --> 39:37.574
This is a friend
helping a friend.

39:39.745 --> 39:40.844
It looks heavy.

39:41.847 --> 39:43.480
I'm fine, thank you.

40:05.036 --> 40:05.635
Let me give you a hand.

40:10.175 --> 40:13.977
So this widow,
where does she live?

40:13.979 --> 40:16.479
Way down in the valley.
I can manage.

40:16.815 --> 40:17.947
How far?

40:18.717 --> 40:22.018
Three... Five kilometers.

40:22.020 --> 40:23.119
It's nothing.

40:24.423 --> 40:26.790
Besides, a little walk
will do me good.

40:29.194 --> 40:31.861
Where I live, Jo...
It's Jo, right?

40:33.198 --> 40:35.799
We too are surrounded
by mountains and trees,

40:35.801 --> 40:37.434
so this is like home.

40:38.970 --> 40:41.504
If she sees you with it,
I won't get my honey.

40:42.641 --> 40:43.773
Honey?

40:43.775 --> 40:45.842
The widow,
she pays me with it.

40:45.844 --> 40:48.745
If she sees you carrying
one of the bags,
I won't get any.

40:49.915 --> 40:52.682
I haven't had honey
since I left home.

40:53.685 --> 40:55.552
Apple blossom honey.

40:55.554 --> 40:57.687
That's what my wife makes.

40:57.689 --> 41:00.056
And my girls,
I have three daughters.

41:00.058 --> 41:01.658
They eat it so fast.

41:02.561 --> 41:04.594
If I'm lucky,

41:04.596 --> 41:06.529
they leave me
a spoon to lick.

41:06.531 --> 41:08.031
Especially my oldest, Anna.

41:08.800 --> 41:10.900
She's the clever one.

41:10.902 --> 41:13.770
She goes to Berlin
to work the telephones.

41:13.772 --> 41:16.005
[SIREN SOUNDING]

41:19.478 --> 41:22.946
Well, no honey for me today.

41:22.948 --> 41:24.914
But one day,
I shall taste it.

41:26.885 --> 41:28.852
I'm like a bear, Jo.

41:28.854 --> 41:31.020
I like honey,
and I like mountains.

41:32.157 --> 41:34.224
In my mountains,
we have bears

41:35.694 --> 41:38.495
-and eagles.
-Oh, we have eagles, too.

41:39.865 --> 41:42.065
Well, we should go
up there someday.

41:42.067 --> 41:44.834
You and me.
Look at the eagles

41:44.836 --> 41:46.102
with my binoculars.

41:47.005 --> 41:48.171
Would you like that?

41:49.908 --> 41:51.074
So it's a promise.

41:53.712 --> 41:55.011
<i> Wiedersehen,</i> Jo.

41:56.248 --> 41:57.714
You know what that means?

41:59.184 --> 42:00.517
Until we meet again.

42:17.168 --> 42:18.234
What?

42:19.871 --> 42:22.038
We need you to bring
your grandpere up here.

42:22.040 --> 42:23.573
What... Why?

42:23.575 --> 42:25.608
We have six children
in the barn.

42:25.610 --> 42:27.277
The cow has gone dry,

42:27.279 --> 42:29.746
and this is our last
jar of honey.

42:29.748 --> 42:32.015
After a week,
we won't have anything.

42:32.017 --> 42:33.683
So the pigs will have to go.

42:34.219 --> 42:36.019
With the money we make,

42:36.020 --> 42:37.820
maybe we can survive
for another few months.

42:39.090 --> 42:40.890
But what about Benjamin?

42:42.127 --> 42:43.693
I'll be out of sight.

42:43.695 --> 42:45.962
As will the children.

42:45.964 --> 42:48.064
What Henri doesn't know
won't hurt him.

42:49.234 --> 42:51.734
Grandpere won't buy the pigs.
He's a shepherd.

42:51.736 --> 42:53.036
He can't stand
the smell of them.

42:53.038 --> 42:54.270
Don't you worry!

42:54.272 --> 42:56.005
You just bring
your grandpere up here.

42:56.975 --> 43:00.010
[SCOFFS]

43:00.011 --> 43:03.046
OLD JO:<i> I couldn't believe it</i>
<i> when Grandpere</i>
<i> bought the pigs.</i>

43:03.048 --> 43:04.747
<i> No one could.</i>

43:04.749 --> 43:07.500
<i> They were the talk</i>
<i> of the village.</i>

43:07.501 --> 43:10.252
<i> More than the Germans,</i>
<i> who were proving</i>
<i> difficult to hate.</i>

43:11.756 --> 43:14.757
<i> I tried my best</i>
<i> for Papa's sake, mostly.</i>

43:14.759 --> 43:17.293
<i> But they came to Mass,</i>
<i> gave us sweets,</i>

43:17.295 --> 43:18.895
<i> played pelota.</i>

43:18.897 --> 43:22.165
<i> It was easy to forget</i>
<i> why they were there.</i>

43:24.603 --> 43:27.737
"She could not have been a good,
honest old woman,

43:27.739 --> 43:29.639
"for first she looked
in at the window,

43:29.641 --> 43:31.341
"and then she peeped in
at the keyhole,

43:32.911 --> 43:35.979
"and seeing nobody
in the house,
she lifted the latch.

43:35.981 --> 43:37.680
"The door was not fastened.

43:39.718 --> 43:41.818
"Because the bears
were good bears

43:41.820 --> 43:43.319
"who did nobody harm."

44:01.272 --> 44:03.706
[ROUF BARKS]

44:07.178 --> 44:08.945
What do you think
you're doing?

44:08.947 --> 44:10.213
Out of my way.

44:13.184 --> 44:14.784
What is going on?

44:15.920 --> 44:17.687
-Maman!
-What's this all about?

44:18.690 --> 44:20.723
We are searching
all houses.

44:20.725 --> 44:23.426
What on Earth
are you looking for?
We have nothing to hide.

44:23.428 --> 44:25.361
Orders from
Lieutenant Weissmann.

44:31.269 --> 44:32.969
Don't touch that.
They're private!

44:32.971 --> 44:34.203
Excuse me.

44:38.243 --> 44:40.443
[PEOPLE ARGUE IN DISTANCE]

44:45.050 --> 44:47.850
From a labor camp.
Your husband?

44:47.852 --> 44:49.919
He's a prisoner of war.

44:49.921 --> 44:52.321
He choose to fight
against the Germans, Fraulein.

44:52.323 --> 44:54.857
Is that a letter from Papa?

44:54.859 --> 44:58.461
Maybe his son, too,
wants to fight
against the Germans.

44:58.463 --> 44:59.829
Maybe I will.

45:01.366 --> 45:02.799
Why didn't you tell me, Maman?

45:02.801 --> 45:03.933
They're not his words.

45:03.935 --> 45:05.168
The guards write the letters.

45:05.170 --> 45:06.235
I want to read.

45:06.237 --> 45:08.004
-Stop that, Jo!
-I want to read!

45:12.277 --> 45:13.943
[DOG BARKING]

45:31.396 --> 45:32.762
[CHUCKLES]

45:32.764 --> 45:33.863
Grandpere?

45:33.865 --> 45:35.431
What the devil
are you doing here?

45:35.433 --> 45:37.200
Soldiers.
They're searching houses.

45:37.202 --> 45:39.902
-How far?
-I don't know. Soon.

45:43.308 --> 45:46.309
Henri, you warned me
this day would come.

45:46.311 --> 45:49.112
For the first time in my life,
I wish I was wrong.

45:49.114 --> 45:50.980
-You better go.
-I'm not leaving you.

45:50.982 --> 45:53.249
I have young Jo here
to keep me safe.

45:55.854 --> 45:57.320
Jo, fetch some bread.

45:57.322 --> 46:00.123
You have to eat.
Boys are always eating.

46:05.063 --> 46:07.363
What about Benjamin
and the children?

46:07.365 --> 46:08.831
I'll worry about them.

46:14.439 --> 46:16.439
I'm sorry, madame.
It just came out.

46:16.441 --> 46:18.274
Don't be sorry about a thing.

46:18.276 --> 46:19.876
Your grandfather's an old goat,

46:19.878 --> 46:21.944
but he's a hard man
to lie to.

46:23.047 --> 46:25.181
He knows?

46:25.183 --> 46:28.885
Honest men, like honest boys,
are very hard to find.

46:29.287 --> 46:30.353
Go on, eat.

46:42.133 --> 46:43.800
So why was he only wearing...

46:43.802 --> 46:44.934
Eat, Jo.

46:48.373 --> 46:49.438
Madame.

46:50.508 --> 46:53.843
[GUARDS SPEAK GERMAN]

46:56.214 --> 46:57.947
He's your grandson?

46:57.949 --> 46:59.448
He's my shopping boy.

46:59.450 --> 47:01.083
[RUMBLING OVERHEAD]

47:02.220 --> 47:04.587
Fire, huh?

47:04.589 --> 47:06.122
[RUMBLING CONTINUES]

47:06.524 --> 47:07.924
[THUDS]

47:15.200 --> 47:17.133
As you can see,
he's quite useful.

47:23.341 --> 47:25.107
You live alone?

47:25.109 --> 47:26.409
Apart from the pigs?

47:26.411 --> 47:28.945
My husband died
in the Great War.

47:28.947 --> 47:30.279
"The Great War."
[SNICKERS]

47:31.082 --> 47:33.266
Strange that in my homeland,

47:33.267 --> 47:35.451
it isn't referred to
in such favorable parlance.

47:37.088 --> 47:40.356
My I offer you a drink,
Lieutenant?

47:40.358 --> 47:41.858
Coffee, please.

47:43.595 --> 47:45.361
[RUMBLING]

47:50.535 --> 47:52.435
Very useful, indeed.

47:52.437 --> 47:54.370
You have to tell me
where I can get one.

47:59.377 --> 48:01.544
I want mine to have
a steady hand, though.

48:03.147 --> 48:04.280
Like mine.

48:05.083 --> 48:07.016
German stability.

48:07.018 --> 48:09.118
Why are you searching
our houses?

48:09.120 --> 48:11.988
It's a fair question
shopping boy's asking.

48:13.992 --> 48:16.259
There's been a theft
from the barracks.

48:16.261 --> 48:17.927
Munitions have been stolen.

48:19.063 --> 48:22.231
Explosives that,
in the wrong hands,

48:22.233 --> 48:23.933
could be used against us.

48:27.105 --> 48:30.673
After the fairness with which
we have treated the people
of Lescun,

48:30.675 --> 48:32.208
it would be quite
a stab in the back

48:32.210 --> 48:33.676
for the village
to turn against us.

48:36.080 --> 48:39.015
So the sooner we can
find what's been taken,

48:39.017 --> 48:42.084
the sooner I can put
the individuals responsible
against the wall,

48:42.987 --> 48:44.253
and the rest of us

48:45.556 --> 48:47.924
can all go back
to being friends again.

48:48.192 --> 48:49.358
Yeah?

48:50.595 --> 48:52.428
[SPEAKING GERMAN]

48:59.037 --> 49:00.369
After you, madame. Please.

49:08.980 --> 49:12.281
You know,
I really don't like farms,
shopping boy.

49:13.451 --> 49:14.617
They stink.

49:15.453 --> 49:17.420
Stink of shit. It amazes me

49:17.422 --> 49:20.523
how you people spend your lives
surrounded by stinking animals.

49:22.627 --> 49:24.293
But if I had something to hide,

49:25.263 --> 49:27.029
I would put it
somewhere that stinks.

49:28.399 --> 49:30.599
Clever thinking,
wouldn't you say so,
shopping boy?

49:30.601 --> 49:32.234
-[HORSE WHINNIES]
-Jo.

49:33.004 --> 49:34.136
Jo?

49:34.138 --> 49:35.571
My name is Jo, monsieur.

49:35.573 --> 49:37.540
Jo. Okay.

49:37.542 --> 49:40.509
Please, he's just a child.
He's innocent.

49:40.511 --> 49:42.044
Oh, I understand.

49:42.046 --> 49:43.980
He's your lifeblood.

49:43.982 --> 49:46.349
Bring you all that shopping,
week in and week out.

49:46.351 --> 49:47.483
Rain or shine.

49:48.419 --> 49:50.486
You're protective of him.

49:50.488 --> 49:52.121
Why you're knitting him
the jumper.

49:53.191 --> 49:54.557
It is for him, I assume.

49:55.560 --> 49:57.159
I do hope it fits you, Jo.

50:01.366 --> 50:02.598
[SPEAKS GERMAN]

50:09.507 --> 50:10.573
That's mine.

50:11.342 --> 50:12.708
Give the boy his book, then.

50:16.414 --> 50:17.780
Read to me a little.

50:17.782 --> 50:19.448
A boy with a book
can surely read.

50:29.494 --> 50:32.728
"Once upon a time
in a large forest,

50:32.730 --> 50:34.530
"close to a village,

50:34.532 --> 50:36.198
"three bears lived.

50:37.668 --> 50:39.769
"A great big papa bear,

50:39.771 --> 50:41.771
"a middle-sized maman bear,

50:42.740 --> 50:45.408
"and a wee little baby bear."

50:48.112 --> 50:50.413
A shopping boy
and a scholar!

50:50.415 --> 50:52.681
[CHUCKLES] I really must
get myself one.

50:55.253 --> 50:56.452
Madame.

51:05.096 --> 51:06.362
Where are they, madame?

51:29.487 --> 51:31.320
-[COUGHS]
-HENRI: Who is it?

51:33.624 --> 51:35.458
[SPEAKS FRENCH]

51:35.726 --> 51:37.226
Grandpere?

51:40.231 --> 51:41.464
Leah!

51:41.466 --> 51:42.731
Hello, Leah!

51:46.337 --> 51:47.870
[COUGHS]

51:48.673 --> 51:50.339
How long have you been here?

51:50.341 --> 51:52.575
Almost one month now.

51:52.577 --> 51:54.276
It was all
your grandpa's idea.

51:54.278 --> 51:57.413
My father's old brandy store.

51:57.415 --> 52:01.550
Your great-grandfather used
to do a bit of smuggling

52:01.552 --> 52:02.885
when I was your age.

52:04.355 --> 52:06.522
Perfect for hiding things.

52:07.625 --> 52:09.692
It is safe for now.

52:09.694 --> 52:11.560
But today was
a warning, Alice.

52:12.830 --> 52:16.198
We've got to get the children
across the border.

52:16.200 --> 52:18.300
No. We have to be patient.

52:18.302 --> 52:20.836
We bide our time
as agreed.

52:20.838 --> 52:22.505
You might make it
on your own, Henri,

52:22.507 --> 52:24.473
but not with the children.

52:25.743 --> 52:27.176
We have to wait.

52:32.150 --> 52:33.766
That's all we can do.

52:33.767 --> 52:35.383
I have never been able
to persuade that woman

52:35.386 --> 52:38.220
around to my way
of thinking.

52:39.857 --> 52:42.224
-Why didn't you tell me?
-Tell you what?

52:45.163 --> 52:47.263
Because she told me not to.

52:47.265 --> 52:50.599
And because sometimes,
it is safer not to know.

52:52.403 --> 52:54.603
And why didn't you tell me?

52:54.939 --> 52:56.305
Same reason.

52:58.442 --> 53:01.377
-And remember...
-Not a word to Maman.

53:01.379 --> 53:04.446
Not with a hundred
of bleating sheep around us.

53:04.782 --> 53:06.182
Ha!

53:11.756 --> 53:13.722
Hello, Hubert. Hello, Jo.

53:14.959 --> 53:16.725
Haven't seen you
the past weeks.

53:17.595 --> 53:19.562
Busy with the lambs?

53:19.564 --> 53:20.829
Grandpere does most of it.

53:21.599 --> 53:22.898
[LAUGHS]

53:22.900 --> 53:25.401
The old man with the newborn

53:25.403 --> 53:27.369
and you down here
swinging the hammer?

53:30.708 --> 53:32.908
Widen your stance.
Get more power.

53:32.910 --> 53:34.610
Don't need your help.

53:37.915 --> 53:40.816
-Do you wanna look?
-[CHUCKLES] Yeah.

53:41.953 --> 53:44.286
I told you on Fridays
I have a few hours off.

53:44.288 --> 53:46.689
-[GIGGLES]
-I do not forget my promise.

53:47.491 --> 53:48.624
What promise?

53:48.926 --> 53:49.992
The eagles.

53:54.298 --> 53:55.431
Take Hubert.

53:56.567 --> 53:57.900
As you wish.

53:57.902 --> 53:59.835
Hubert, you wanna come
look for eagles?

53:59.837 --> 54:02.238
-[CHUCKLES]
-Let's go.

54:11.549 --> 54:13.983
OLD JO:<i> Grandpere was</i>
<i> always telling me,</i>

54:13.985 --> 54:16.952
<i> hard work is good</i>
<i> for the soul.</i>

54:16.954 --> 54:19.888
<i> But not matter how hard</i>
<i> I swung the hammer,</i>

54:19.890 --> 54:21.757
<i> my anger remained.</i>

54:21.759 --> 54:25.261
<i>I couldn't forgive the Corporal</i>
<i> for what he was part of.</i>

54:25.263 --> 54:27.696
Jo, Jo! [CHUCKLES]

54:27.698 --> 54:30.466
Eagle! Eagle! [GIGGLES]

54:30.468 --> 54:32.835
I don't know where he gets
his energy. I'm exhausted.

54:32.837 --> 54:35.304
-Eagle!
-You saw the eagle, didn't you?

54:36.340 --> 54:37.706
Eagle. [CHUCKLES]

54:37.708 --> 54:39.575
Hubert spotted her first.

54:39.577 --> 54:42.044
On the ground she was. Proud.

54:42.046 --> 54:43.746
On the rock, like a stag.

54:45.683 --> 54:47.449
She took off as we approached.

54:48.853 --> 54:50.853
So we followed her
up the mountains...

54:50.855 --> 54:52.721
-[GIGGLES]
-...till she nested.

54:54.425 --> 54:55.524
You found her nest?

54:56.060 --> 54:57.827
Yes, we did.

54:57.828 --> 54:59.595
What about her young?
Did you see any chicks?

54:59.597 --> 55:00.729
Not this time.

55:01.465 --> 55:02.598
Maybe next week.

55:07.371 --> 55:08.871
<i> Auf wiedersehen.</i>

55:08.873 --> 55:10.072
<i> Wiedersehen,</i> Jo.

55:12.810 --> 55:14.710
Eagle. Eagle's nest.

55:14.712 --> 55:16.011
[GIGGLES] Yeah.

55:17.682 --> 55:20.015
[MUMBLES]

55:20.651 --> 55:22.418
[KIDS LAUGHING]

55:22.420 --> 55:24.086
[SOLDIERS SPEAKING GERMAN]

55:59.957 --> 56:01.924
Did you hear about
the Allies bombing Berlin?

56:02.993 --> 56:04.727
His daughter was there.

56:04.729 --> 56:06.028
She did not
stand a chance.

56:41.632 --> 56:44.166
I'm sorry about what happened
to your daughter.

56:48.773 --> 56:50.739
Do you like poetry, Jo?

56:53.444 --> 56:55.878
Silly question.
I don't like it much either.

56:59.650 --> 57:01.417
But there's one poem.

57:01.419 --> 57:03.419
A German poem
about the mountains.

57:05.489 --> 57:07.956
"Over all the hills,
peace comes anew

57:09.193 --> 57:12.628
"The woodlands still
all through.

57:12.630 --> 57:14.863
"The birds make no sound
on the bough.

57:17.768 --> 57:19.635
"Wait a while, soon now...

57:22.940 --> 57:24.473
"peace comes to you."

57:25.776 --> 57:27.576
-It's...
-It's a lie.

57:29.513 --> 57:31.613
Some things,
even the mountains cannot solve.

57:38.856 --> 57:40.989
Since I hear about
my daughter, Jo,

57:45.129 --> 57:47.095
every day, I ask myself
many questions.

57:48.799 --> 57:51.099
It's the easy part.
Answering them, no so much.

57:53.070 --> 57:54.803
"What are you doing here,
Wilhelm?"

57:58.008 --> 58:00.142
"I'm guarding the frontier."

58:00.144 --> 58:01.210
"Why?"

58:03.147 --> 58:04.246
"Simple.

58:05.850 --> 58:08.050
"To keep the Jews
from escaping."

58:10.855 --> 58:13.522
"But why do they
want to escape?"

58:13.524 --> 58:15.824
"Because they fear
for their lives."

58:15.826 --> 58:17.593
"And who threatens
their lives?"

58:19.196 --> 58:20.262
"I do."

58:23.834 --> 58:25.701
"And what happens
when they get captured?"

58:26.237 --> 58:27.669
"Concentration camp."

58:29.573 --> 58:31.607
"And what happens there,
Wilhelm?"

58:40.084 --> 58:41.683
How do you answer that, Jo?

59:29.567 --> 59:31.833
At least we achieved
something today.

1:00:18.716 --> 1:00:20.749
[SIREN BLARING]

1:00:20.751 --> 1:00:22.651
Why are you punishing us all?

1:00:23.120 --> 1:00:24.653
You can't...

1:00:24.655 --> 1:00:26.088
-[SPEAKS GERMAN]
-Stop it!

1:00:26.090 --> 1:00:27.222
Where's the food?

1:00:28.092 --> 1:00:30.826
No, please.

1:00:30.828 --> 1:00:32.628
You can't take it!

1:00:32.630 --> 1:00:34.896
It won't be anyone
in the village.

1:00:34.898 --> 1:00:36.064
[SPEAKS GERMAN]

1:00:42.406 --> 1:00:44.339
Boys, I'm afraid I'm very busy.

1:00:44.341 --> 1:00:45.674
You really mustn't come here.

1:00:49.413 --> 1:00:51.680
And we are not to go
looking for eagles again.

1:00:51.682 --> 1:00:53.315
The Lieutenant
has forbidden it.

1:00:57.021 --> 1:00:58.820
[MUMBLES]

1:01:00.324 --> 1:01:01.790
You know my brand.

1:01:03.060 --> 1:01:05.427
Thank you, Hubert.
That's very kind.

1:01:06.330 --> 1:01:08.163
Hubert wants you
to open them.

1:01:11.902 --> 1:01:14.302
I'm really not
in the mood for jokes.

1:01:16.740 --> 1:01:19.007
-What is this?
-He makes them.

1:02:09.259 --> 1:02:10.726
[MUMBLES]

1:02:14.131 --> 1:02:16.765
[CHUCKLES GLEEFULLY]

1:02:16.767 --> 1:02:19.901
Run along now, the pair of you.
I really must get back to work.

1:02:20.270 --> 1:02:22.237
[CHUCKLES]

1:02:33.851 --> 1:02:36.084
No. Stop it!

1:02:36.086 --> 1:02:37.786
Just leave this.
Just leave this!

1:02:39.423 --> 1:02:41.490
There are no
resistance fighters here.

1:02:43.060 --> 1:02:44.493
Please, not the vegetables!

1:02:52.136 --> 1:02:53.902
[COUGHING]

1:03:05.048 --> 1:03:07.015
Have they said
when the line will be open?

1:03:07.017 --> 1:03:10.185
Nobody knows.
Not even the Germans.

1:03:10.187 --> 1:03:13.088
So they steal our food
and leave us to starve.

1:03:13.090 --> 1:03:15.190
No one's going to starve.

1:03:15.192 --> 1:03:17.125
We're going to get
the children into Spain.

1:03:17.127 --> 1:03:19.194
Don't be naive, Benjamin.

1:03:19.196 --> 1:03:21.396
Are you going to do that
with a sick child?

1:03:23.300 --> 1:03:27.002
Jo, were you at least able
to buy the medicine
I asked for?

1:03:28.372 --> 1:03:29.971
I'm sorry, Lukas.

1:03:31.308 --> 1:03:32.874
I'm really sorry.

1:03:33.277 --> 1:03:34.509
[LUKAS WHEEZING]

1:03:50.594 --> 1:03:52.360
You see, Jo, like us,

1:03:52.362 --> 1:03:54.396
they thrive
where there's no light.

1:03:56.466 --> 1:03:58.099
A few more of these,
and we'll have enough

1:03:58.101 --> 1:04:00.068
to make Lukas
a pot of mushroom tea.

1:04:02.005 --> 1:04:03.572
We'll soon have him
breathing better.

1:04:04.608 --> 1:04:07.242
-What did you do?
-Me?

1:04:07.244 --> 1:04:09.477
All of you.
Why do they hate you so much?

1:04:11.849 --> 1:04:13.315
If the Tiber rises too high,

1:04:13.317 --> 1:04:15.851
the Nile sinks too low,

1:04:15.853 --> 1:04:18.119
the cry is always,
"The Christian to the lion."

1:04:19.990 --> 1:04:21.923
They hate us because they can.

1:04:22.626 --> 1:04:23.992
And do you hate them?

1:04:28.498 --> 1:04:29.564
I pity them.

1:04:33.937 --> 1:04:38.607
"One day, after they
made their porridge
for their breakfast,

1:04:38.609 --> 1:04:41.209
"and poured it
into their porridge bowls,

1:04:42.179 --> 1:04:43.645
"they walked out
into the wood

1:04:43.647 --> 1:04:45.947
"while their porridge
was cooling."

1:04:45.949 --> 1:04:49.251
OLD JO:<i> I have to admit</i>
<i> that, at the time,</i>

1:04:49.253 --> 1:04:52.387
<i> I didn't understand</i>
<i> what Benjamin meant</i>

1:04:52.389 --> 1:04:54.489
<i> when he talked about</i>
<i> the Nile and the Tiber</i>

1:04:54.491 --> 1:04:56.892
<i> and the Christians</i>
<i> and the lion.</i>

1:04:56.894 --> 1:04:59.527
"She could not have been
a good, honest woman..."

1:04:59.529 --> 1:05:01.930
<i> But I soon learned</i>
<i> to pity a man</i>

1:05:01.932 --> 1:05:04.232
<i> if he's so full of hate,</i>

1:05:04.234 --> 1:05:07.602
<i> as one returned</i>
<i> to live in my home.</i>

1:05:07.604 --> 1:05:09.971
There's someone here
to see you, Jo.

1:05:13.277 --> 1:05:14.576
Papa!

1:05:18.982 --> 1:05:20.548
At least you
recognize me, huh?

1:05:21.652 --> 1:05:22.918
MAMAN: You can't
blame Christine.

1:05:22.920 --> 1:05:24.319
She was only two
when you left us.

1:05:26.356 --> 1:05:27.956
Let me look at you, hmm?

1:05:32.162 --> 1:05:33.461
You have grown so much.

1:05:36.266 --> 1:05:37.399
Come here.

1:05:44.574 --> 1:05:46.675
Jo. Grandpere.

1:05:57.020 --> 1:05:58.954
That might look
like a crippled hand, Jo.

1:06:00.023 --> 1:06:02.357
But to me,
that was my ticket home.

1:06:04.261 --> 1:06:07.495
The Germans sent him home
because the bastards
couldn't work him anymore.

1:06:09.399 --> 1:06:10.465
Bedtime, Christine.

1:06:10.467 --> 1:06:12.167
-No, no, no.
-No.

1:06:12.169 --> 1:06:13.401
You go to bed now, please.

1:06:13.403 --> 1:06:15.704
Listen to your mother,
young lady.

1:06:15.706 --> 1:06:17.339
Let her stay
a little longer, Lise.

1:06:19.109 --> 1:06:21.276
Well, it's late.
It's been a long day.

1:06:21.278 --> 1:06:22.978
And it's a special occasion.

1:06:23.747 --> 1:06:25.747
My father just came home. Hmm?

1:06:27.117 --> 1:06:29.651
Jo stepped right
into your shoes.

1:06:29.653 --> 1:06:32.220
You would have been
real proud of him.

1:06:32.222 --> 1:06:34.522
Maybe he's missed school
more often that he should have,

1:06:34.524 --> 1:06:37.058
but Mademoiselle Audap
understands.

1:06:37.060 --> 1:06:39.260
-Who?
-My teacher.

1:06:39.262 --> 1:06:41.663
She replaced Monsieur Balis
after you left.

1:06:42.599 --> 1:06:44.599
And Hubert helped him,
of course.

1:06:44.601 --> 1:06:46.201
You remember Hubert?

1:06:47.037 --> 1:06:48.636
Of course I do.

1:06:48.638 --> 1:06:52.507
And I didn't exactly sit
on my behind for four years.

1:06:52.509 --> 1:06:55.710
You looked after more than
just the sheep
in those mountains, Henri.

1:06:55.712 --> 1:06:57.012
What is this?

1:06:57.014 --> 1:06:58.413
Your father's been courting.

1:06:59.449 --> 1:07:02.050
Courting? Who?

1:07:04.187 --> 1:07:05.687
MAMAN: Widow Horcada.

1:07:05.689 --> 1:07:08.189
PAPA: Again? I don't believe it.

1:07:12.462 --> 1:07:14.129
-Where are you going?
-Out.

1:07:14.131 --> 1:07:15.730
But you can't. It's late.

1:07:15.732 --> 1:07:17.499
And you're not well.

1:07:17.500 --> 1:07:19.267
There's a curfew. If the Boche
catch you, they'll...

1:07:19.269 --> 1:07:21.069
They'll do what, Papa?

1:07:21.071 --> 1:07:23.171
Lock me up? Shoot me?

1:07:24.307 --> 1:07:26.241
Four years I was in that camp.

1:07:26.243 --> 1:07:29.310
I won't let them make
a prisoner of me
in my own home.

1:07:29.312 --> 1:07:30.812
MAMAN: Please, Georges!

1:07:30.814 --> 1:07:32.247
I don't want to lose you again.

1:07:32.249 --> 1:07:33.314
-Okay.
-CHRISTINE: Papa!

1:07:33.316 --> 1:07:34.382
HENRI: Georges!

1:07:34.384 --> 1:07:36.084
[RECEDING FOOTSTEPS]

1:07:56.540 --> 1:07:58.073
Please, please. Continue.

1:08:12.689 --> 1:08:14.722
OLD JO:<i> When the church doors</i>
<i> were open</i>

1:08:14.724 --> 1:08:18.293
<i> and the village square</i>
<i> was filled with</i>
<i> the sound of Bach,</i>

1:08:18.295 --> 1:08:21.863
<i> we knew that summer</i>
<i> was fast approaching.</i>

1:08:21.865 --> 1:08:25.433
<i> Father Lasalle's music</i>
<i> seemed to lift the spirits</i>

1:08:25.435 --> 1:08:27.635
<i> of the entire parish.</i>

1:08:27.637 --> 1:08:29.404
<i> All except the Corporal,</i>

1:08:29.406 --> 1:08:31.840
<i>who would sit outside the cafe,</i>

1:08:31.842 --> 1:08:34.209
<i> consumed with questions</i>

1:08:34.211 --> 1:08:37.145
<i> while my Papa drank inside.</i>

1:08:49.493 --> 1:08:51.559
[CHEERFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

1:09:17.187 --> 1:09:18.253
SOLDIER: Three beers, please.

1:09:26.596 --> 1:09:29.264
Look who came to
welcome me back home.

1:09:29.266 --> 1:09:30.698
Hmm? [SPEAKING GERMAN]

1:09:32.702 --> 1:09:34.169
Good evening.

1:09:34.171 --> 1:09:35.570
You must join our little party.

1:09:50.554 --> 1:09:51.619
To victory.

1:09:55.759 --> 1:09:56.824
To peace.

1:09:58.295 --> 1:09:59.460
Binocular.

1:10:02.566 --> 1:10:03.648
Not now, Hubert.

1:10:03.649 --> 1:10:04.731
And where did you
get them, Hubert? Hmm?

1:10:04.734 --> 1:10:06.601
-Where did you
get them, Hubert, huh?
-Papa!

1:10:06.603 --> 1:10:08.670
-What?
-The Corporal.

1:10:08.672 --> 1:10:10.939
He's a friend of yours, too?
Hmm?

1:10:15.278 --> 1:10:16.344
Good night.

1:10:17.747 --> 1:10:19.247
<i> Auf wiedersehen.</i>

1:10:27.958 --> 1:10:29.357
It's okay.

1:11:09.866 --> 1:11:10.999
[GASPS]

1:11:11.768 --> 1:11:12.867
Georges?

1:11:13.570 --> 1:11:16.271
Ah. [CHUCKLES]

1:11:16.273 --> 1:11:17.839
Come back to bed, Georges.

1:11:18.308 --> 1:11:19.941
Hilarious.

1:11:19.943 --> 1:11:21.376
Give me that.

1:11:21.378 --> 1:11:24.445
[GROANS]

1:11:24.447 --> 1:11:26.748
I've been hearing things
about you I don't like, Jo.

1:11:26.750 --> 1:11:28.016
Leave him be.

1:11:28.018 --> 1:11:31.386
I said, I've been
hearing things

1:11:31.388 --> 1:11:32.654
I don't like, Jo.

1:11:32.656 --> 1:11:34.689
Don't you dare blame
my boy for any of this.

1:11:34.691 --> 1:11:36.675
Your boy?
You can have him.

1:11:36.676 --> 1:11:38.660
-Take that back.
-You stay out of this.

1:11:38.662 --> 1:11:40.595
Michel, he told me how
you went off

1:11:40.597 --> 1:11:43.498
with that German Corporal
up the mountain together.

1:11:43.500 --> 1:11:46.034
I was only watching eagles.

1:11:46.036 --> 1:11:47.935
Eagles? My own son,

1:11:48.805 --> 1:11:51.806
friends with the filthy Boche?

1:11:54.411 --> 1:11:55.743
You're a collaborator.

1:11:57.380 --> 1:11:59.847
-And you're a monster!
-Eh?

1:11:59.849 --> 1:12:02.517
Stop it, Georges!
You think it was easy for us?

1:12:02.519 --> 1:12:04.519
-We have to survive!
-Georges, enough.

1:12:04.521 --> 1:12:07.322
Let me tell you something
about your son.

1:12:07.324 --> 1:12:09.457
-No, no, no!
-This "collaborator."

1:12:09.459 --> 1:12:10.925
MAMAN: What's going on?
JO: Please, don't, please.

1:12:10.927 --> 1:12:13.394
You know how Jo does
Alice's shopping?

1:12:13.396 --> 1:12:14.462
And what?

1:12:14.464 --> 1:12:15.863
That food is
not for Alice.

1:12:16.733 --> 1:12:18.566
It is for seven children.

1:12:18.568 --> 1:12:19.967
Seven Jewish children,

1:12:19.969 --> 1:12:22.704
hiding in a cave,
up in the woods.

1:12:22.706 --> 1:12:24.972
Some of them have been
waiting two years,

1:12:24.974 --> 1:12:27.108
near enough to be taken
over the border.

1:12:27.744 --> 1:12:28.910
All that time,

1:12:28.912 --> 1:12:31.546
your son has been
keeping them alive.

1:12:32.515 --> 1:12:34.515
Not only he's kept them alive,

1:12:34.517 --> 1:12:36.551
but he's kept his mouth shut!

1:12:37.087 --> 1:12:39.053
So don't you ever call him

1:12:39.055 --> 1:12:41.589
a collaborator again!

1:12:41.591 --> 1:12:42.990
MAMAN: I can't believe this.

1:12:42.992 --> 1:12:44.892
How can you
keep this from me?

1:12:44.894 --> 1:12:47.428
Because you, you would have
only tried to stop him!

1:12:53.870 --> 1:12:55.470
But these poor children,

1:12:58.875 --> 1:13:00.325
are they still in the cave?

1:13:00.326 --> 1:13:01.776
A patrol could find them
at any moment.

1:13:01.778 --> 1:13:03.578
You think we want
to keep them there?

1:13:04.814 --> 1:13:07.548
There's just no way
to get seven children

1:13:07.550 --> 1:13:09.817
past the patrols
without being seen.

1:13:11.454 --> 1:13:12.820
Well, maybe
you don't have to.

1:13:14.991 --> 1:13:17.558
People see what
they want to see.

1:13:18.595 --> 1:13:20.628
They're too lazy to look
for anything else.

1:13:22.432 --> 1:13:25.800
Take a man
drinking before noon,
he's a drunk,

1:13:26.703 --> 1:13:27.935
not a grieving husband.

1:13:29.839 --> 1:13:33.908
And an old spinster in black
is a widow, not a saint.

1:13:35.678 --> 1:13:39.514
And a boy laden with shopping
is an errand boy,

1:13:40.450 --> 1:13:41.516
not a hero.

1:13:43.186 --> 1:13:44.986
What are you
getting at, Lise?

1:13:46.589 --> 1:13:47.655
Well,

1:13:49.893 --> 1:13:50.958
a child

1:13:51.995 --> 1:13:53.060
herding sheep

1:13:54.130 --> 1:13:55.196
is a shepherd.

1:13:56.599 --> 1:13:57.665
Not a Jew.

1:13:59.736 --> 1:14:00.835
You're mad!

1:14:00.837 --> 1:14:03.671
Disguise children
as shepherds?

1:14:03.673 --> 1:14:04.806
Absolutely not!

1:14:04.808 --> 1:14:06.808
Madame.

1:14:06.809 --> 1:14:08.809
There must be
500 sheep in the village.

1:14:08.812 --> 1:14:11.212
It's chaos when we move
to high pastures.

1:14:11.214 --> 1:14:13.648
Who will notice a few more
children shepherding them?

1:14:13.650 --> 1:14:15.583
And once you get to the herds,

1:14:15.585 --> 1:14:18.719
you're that close to Spain,
you could spit into it.

1:14:18.721 --> 1:14:21.222
Everyone knows
only the men
drive the sheep.

1:14:21.224 --> 1:14:22.857
Not the Boche.

1:14:22.859 --> 1:14:24.592
They've been here
two years,

1:14:24.594 --> 1:14:27.094
and couldn't tell
the first thing
about shepherding.

1:14:27.096 --> 1:14:28.629
What if somebody talks?

1:14:28.631 --> 1:14:30.465
You're involving
the entire village.

1:14:30.467 --> 1:14:32.567
It only takes
one person to panic.

1:14:32.569 --> 1:14:34.135
-It's a possibility.
-ALICE: No!

1:14:34.137 --> 1:14:36.204
These are children's lives
we are talking about.

1:14:36.206 --> 1:14:38.639
It's not a possibility.
The answer is no!

1:14:41.511 --> 1:14:43.044
Alice,

1:14:43.046 --> 1:14:44.545
you have
to let them go.

1:14:46.583 --> 1:14:48.483
Henri,

1:14:48.485 --> 1:14:50.051
what if something
happens to them?

1:14:51.154 --> 1:14:53.921
We have waited
long enough.

1:14:53.923 --> 1:14:56.190
This is our best chance!

1:14:56.192 --> 1:14:58.025
How will we get them
down from the cave?

1:14:59.629 --> 1:15:01.629
You may not like
the sound of this.

1:15:02.899 --> 1:15:04.098
And he said,

1:15:05.802 --> 1:15:07.268
"I am the good shepherd.

1:15:09.739 --> 1:15:12.640
"The good shepherd lays down
his life for the sheep."

1:15:15.144 --> 1:15:17.545
John 10:11.

1:15:17.547 --> 1:15:18.613
[CLEARS THROAT]

1:15:19.883 --> 1:15:22.817
For three months,

1:15:22.818 --> 1:15:25.752
every summer our village
loses many of its menfolk
to the mountain.

1:15:28.124 --> 1:15:29.657
LASALLE:<i> It's</i>
<i> a time of solitude,</i>

1:15:32.161 --> 1:15:34.295
<i> a time for reflection,</i>

1:15:37.233 --> 1:15:42.136
<i> and the beginnings</i>
<i> of months of hard work.</i>

1:15:43.907 --> 1:15:46.774
<i> So, in two weeks,</i>

1:15:46.776 --> 1:15:49.677
<i> to celebrate the eve</i>
<i> of this great migration,</i>

1:15:49.679 --> 1:15:52.313
-[CHOIR SINGING]
<i> -Mademoiselle Audap</i>
<i> and the school choir</i>

1:15:52.315 --> 1:15:54.315
<i> will be giving one of their</i>
<i> short concerts,</i>

1:15:54.317 --> 1:15:56.017
<i> and I want you all here.</i>

1:15:57.086 --> 1:15:59.987
A gathering
of the entire community.

1:16:01.291 --> 1:16:02.957
That invitation

1:16:02.959 --> 1:16:05.793
also extends to our
long-term lodgers.

1:16:05.795 --> 1:16:07.795
I know you're
a music lover, Lieutenant,

1:16:07.797 --> 1:16:10.064
and if the whole
village will be here,

1:16:11.668 --> 1:16:12.733
then, why not
the garrison?

1:16:21.110 --> 1:16:22.310
Thank you, Lieutenant.

1:16:23.947 --> 1:16:25.646
The concert will
begin at 8:00.

1:16:25.648 --> 1:16:26.714
Spread the word.

1:16:31.921 --> 1:16:33.220
[BELL DINGING]

1:17:02.085 --> 1:17:03.250
[THUDDING]

1:17:05.288 --> 1:17:06.754
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

1:17:15.198 --> 1:17:16.263
[THUDS]

1:17:35.351 --> 1:17:38.285
[CHOIR SINGING IN FRENCH]

1:17:45.094 --> 1:17:47.728
HENRI: Time to go.
Follow me.

1:17:57.106 --> 1:17:59.306
Let's go. Come on.

1:17:59.308 --> 1:18:00.408
To the village.

1:18:02.111 --> 1:18:03.411
We're going
to the village.

1:18:06.282 --> 1:18:07.348
Let's go.

1:18:09.085 --> 1:18:10.317
[SINGING IN FRENCH]

1:18:27.804 --> 1:18:29.036
[CHOIR SINGING IN FRENCH]

1:18:44.420 --> 1:18:45.753
[DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE]

1:19:06.976 --> 1:19:09.510
<i> Allez!</i>

1:19:25.361 --> 1:19:27.094
Quiet!<i> Allez!</i>

1:19:36.506 --> 1:19:38.038
This way. Wake up!

1:19:41.277 --> 1:19:42.810
[SINGING CONTINUES]

1:19:59.095 --> 1:20:00.961
WOMAN: [WHISPERING]
Come in, quick!

1:20:00.963 --> 1:20:02.062
HENRI: [WHISPERING]
Thank you, Mademoiselle!

1:20:12.475 --> 1:20:16.243
I'm afraid the concert
lasted a little longer
than we all expected.

1:20:16.245 --> 1:20:18.245
Goodnight,
and God bless you.

1:20:18.981 --> 1:20:20.047
[INDISTINCT MUTTERING]

1:20:27.256 --> 1:20:28.556
[KNOCKING AT DOOR]

1:20:29.892 --> 1:20:32.126
-Benjamin and Leah?
-Up in the hayloft.

1:20:32.128 --> 1:20:33.260
And the rest?

1:20:34.263 --> 1:20:35.329
Hidden,

1:20:35.331 --> 1:20:36.864
before the last
church bell rang.

1:20:48.411 --> 1:20:50.578
Quiet, Jo.
She needs some sleep.

1:20:53.316 --> 1:20:55.382
You'll be
in Spain tomorrow.

1:20:58.588 --> 1:20:59.854
No.

1:21:02.291 --> 1:21:05.259
I'll take the children
to the border,
and then come back.

1:21:09.599 --> 1:21:10.931
She's getting close.

1:21:11.634 --> 1:21:12.933
I can feel it.

1:21:15.004 --> 1:21:17.905
I know I won't have to wait
for my Anya much longer.

1:21:17.907 --> 1:21:19.506
But when
she gets here,

1:21:19.508 --> 1:21:21.041
you'll have to go
to Spain.

1:21:22.111 --> 1:21:23.177
Both of you?

1:21:25.481 --> 1:21:27.514
We'll cross the mountains
one last time.

1:21:29.986 --> 1:21:34.989
Maybe buy a farm
somewhere in the hills.

1:21:34.991 --> 1:21:40.294
Somewhere where
we can have cows,
sheep, pigs.

1:21:40.296 --> 1:21:42.897
Alice would never forgive me
if we didn't have pigs.

1:21:45.668 --> 1:21:48.002
And then we can make up
for the time we lost.

1:21:54.477 --> 1:21:55.643
Don't worry, Jo.

1:21:57.513 --> 1:21:59.246
I'm not going
anywhere just yet.

1:22:02.051 --> 1:22:03.684
I wish you didn't
have to go at all.

1:22:08.557 --> 1:22:09.623
[SOBS]

1:22:13.062 --> 1:22:14.228
-[BELLS DINGING]
-[SHEEP BLEATING]

1:22:18.701 --> 1:22:20.334
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

1:22:38.321 --> 1:22:41.155
[IMITATES WOLF GROWLING
AND CHUCKLES]

1:22:43.059 --> 1:22:44.391
[INDISTINCT CHATTER CONTINUES]

1:23:25.034 --> 1:23:26.266
[DOG BARKING]

1:25:53.349 --> 1:25:54.548
JO:<i> Au revoir,</i> Leah.

1:26:02.424 --> 1:26:03.624
[SHEEP BLEATING]

1:26:04.860 --> 1:26:06.193
When will we know?

1:26:06.862 --> 1:26:08.362
By dawn, hopefully.

1:26:09.165 --> 1:26:10.497
Alice will send message.

1:26:11.400 --> 1:26:12.633
When Benjamin returns.

1:26:16.906 --> 1:26:18.205
[MUTTERING]

1:26:19.542 --> 1:26:22.409
Hubert. Hubert. Shh.
Hubert, stay quiet.

1:26:27.349 --> 1:26:30.350
Hard climb
for an old man.

1:26:30.352 --> 1:26:32.219
Then perhaps you should
have stayed down in the village.

1:26:33.189 --> 1:26:35.556
Perhaps. Hello, boys.

1:26:36.292 --> 1:26:37.357
<i> Bonjour.</i>

1:26:38.360 --> 1:26:41.361
You mind if we
fill our canteens?

1:26:41.931 --> 1:26:43.397
I could do
with a drink.

1:26:46.435 --> 1:26:52.406
Be quick. If I remember rightly,
you also like a drink.

1:26:57.346 --> 1:26:58.712
You see, I too
am from the mountains.

1:27:01.217 --> 1:27:05.552
To you the transhumance.
To me, the alpwirtschaft.

1:27:06.755 --> 1:27:09.223
I expect it's the same
the world over.

1:27:12.595 --> 1:27:16.597
Back at home, we have
only the cows and
the horses, no sheep.

1:27:18.000 --> 1:27:19.733
Cows are like yours.

1:27:19.735 --> 1:27:22.502
But the horses,
they have golden
manes and tails,

1:27:22.504 --> 1:27:23.837
we call them
halflingers.

1:27:25.241 --> 1:27:26.974
Just like you,

1:27:26.976 --> 1:27:30.777
we take them up
to the high pastures
in summertime.

1:27:30.779 --> 1:27:33.714
Except of course,
we do not all
go together.

1:27:33.716 --> 1:27:35.782
It's always been done.

1:27:35.784 --> 1:27:38.619
But the women
and children,

1:27:38.621 --> 1:27:40.754
surely have not always
driven the animals?

1:27:43.926 --> 1:27:45.592
You see, in Bavaria,
it's only the men.

1:27:47.596 --> 1:27:48.695
But you?

1:27:51.467 --> 1:27:53.934
You Germans always
ask so many questions?

1:27:53.936 --> 1:27:55.335
We like to be thorough.

1:27:58.374 --> 1:28:00.540
-[SNEEZES]
-So...

1:28:00.542 --> 1:28:02.409
you alone up here
every summer?

1:28:02.878 --> 1:28:04.411
Yes.

1:28:04.413 --> 1:28:05.912
And all this work
you do yourself?

1:28:05.914 --> 1:28:06.980
Everything.

1:28:08.550 --> 1:28:10.050
-[BREATHING HEAVILY]
-CORPORAL: Care to explain?

1:28:11.420 --> 1:28:12.486
-[COUGHS]
-I...

1:28:12.755 --> 1:28:15.656
[COUGHS]

1:28:20.963 --> 1:28:22.296
You were saying?

1:28:24.633 --> 1:28:27.034
Take the donkey down
once a week with the cheese.

1:28:27.036 --> 1:28:28.468
-Pick up the supplies.
-[WIND BLOWING]

1:28:30.039 --> 1:28:31.371
CORPORAL: It must be hard work.

1:28:33.842 --> 1:28:34.975
Hans.

1:28:37.012 --> 1:28:38.478
We need to get going.

1:28:39.682 --> 1:28:41.915
Need to get the boys
back before curfew.

1:28:43.919 --> 1:28:45.085
You should get
that mended.

1:28:48.857 --> 1:28:49.923
Let's go!

1:28:56.432 --> 1:28:59.866
AUDAP: Let's say I have
12 apples. I can't eat...
[CONTINUES INDISTINCTLY]

1:28:59.868 --> 1:29:03.370
[THINKING]<i> By dawn hopefully,</i>
<i> Alice will send message</i>
<i> when Benjamin returns.</i>

1:29:03.372 --> 1:29:05.539
[CLOCK TICKING LOUDLY]

1:29:05.541 --> 1:29:08.842
<i> By dawn hopefully,</i>
<i> Alice will send message</i>
<i> when Benjamin returns.</i>

1:29:10.679 --> 1:29:13.880
<i> By dawn hopefully,</i>
<i> Alice will send message</i>
<i> when Benjamin returns.</i>

1:29:18.520 --> 1:29:19.853
AUDAP: Is everyone following me?

1:29:21.357 --> 1:29:23.023
Jo?

1:29:23.025 --> 1:29:26.026
I don't think you've been
entirely with us
this morning.

1:29:26.028 --> 1:29:29.363
Whilst I appreciate
you're not a natural
mathematician, I...

1:29:29.365 --> 1:29:31.498
-[CHILDREN GASP]
-Jo!

1:29:31.500 --> 1:29:32.966
-Jo! Jo!
-What is it, Hubert?

1:29:32.968 --> 1:29:36.436
-[GROANS] Jo!
-[SHUSHING]

1:29:36.872 --> 1:29:39.106
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

1:29:39.108 --> 1:29:40.774
All of you,
stay where you are.

1:29:45.547 --> 1:29:48.515
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

1:30:00.629 --> 1:30:03.964
-You're Jews?
-We are.

1:30:03.966 --> 1:30:06.166
You'll be escorted
to the station
by Corporal Hoffman.

1:30:07.903 --> 1:30:09.002
Get them a horse.

1:30:10.606 --> 1:30:11.738
You are the Corporal?

1:30:14.109 --> 1:30:16.076
For God's sake,
you want them to walk?

1:30:16.078 --> 1:30:17.177
They can have mine.

1:30:18.113 --> 1:30:19.813
Fetch him, would you?

1:30:19.815 --> 1:30:21.114
Now, please, Jo Lalande.

1:30:34.563 --> 1:30:35.829
[SOBBING]

1:31:24.046 --> 1:31:25.645
BENJAMIN: And then?

1:31:25.647 --> 1:31:26.913
That is not my concern.

1:31:30.919 --> 1:31:32.052
Column, move out.

1:31:38.193 --> 1:31:39.259
Thank you.

1:31:53.575 --> 1:31:55.008
The children?

1:31:55.010 --> 1:31:57.210
-Safe.
-Then what happened?

1:31:58.580 --> 1:31:59.980
What happened, Papa?

1:32:00.916 --> 1:32:02.148
The little girl.

1:32:05.587 --> 1:32:07.153
I've never seen
anything like it.

1:32:09.157 --> 1:32:13.026
[CHILDREN TALKING INDISTINCTLY]

1:32:13.028 --> 1:32:17.197
PAPA:<i> She clung to him like</i>
<i>she would drown if she let go.</i>

1:32:17.199 --> 1:32:18.665
LEAH: I don't want to go!

1:32:23.305 --> 1:32:26.106
PAPA:<i> Jo, we had to</i>
<i> bring her back with us.</i>

1:32:28.076 --> 1:32:29.676
<i> We had to go back</i>
<i> to the hut.</i>

1:32:32.080 --> 1:32:33.847
Benjamin was so calm.

1:32:35.817 --> 1:32:38.685
The donkey bolted immediately.

1:32:39.888 --> 1:32:42.756
Braying loud enough
to wake the dead.

1:32:46.028 --> 1:32:50.130
And your friend,
he didn't flinch.

1:32:51.800 --> 1:32:54.000
He didn't flinch when
that bear came out
of the trees.

1:32:54.703 --> 1:32:56.236
[BEAR GROWLING]

1:32:56.238 --> 1:32:57.971
<i> He looked it</i>
<i> straight in the eye.</i>

1:32:59.207 --> 1:33:01.141
<i> Like he knew it will</i>
<i> not attack them.</i>

1:33:05.080 --> 1:33:06.580
He just wanted
to say hello.

1:33:11.053 --> 1:33:12.719
No milk today,
old friend.

1:33:15.023 --> 1:33:18.191
PAPA: And in one moment,
the bear was gone.

1:33:20.128 --> 1:33:22.696
I went after
the donkey.

1:33:22.698 --> 1:33:25.865
And when I came back,
they were surrounded.

1:33:33.709 --> 1:33:36.309
Someone's got to go
tell Alice.

1:33:36.311 --> 1:33:38.678
And I don't know
if I have the heart.

1:33:39.314 --> 1:33:41.648
We'll go together.

1:33:41.650 --> 1:33:44.184
Then better get yourself
back up the mountains.

1:33:44.186 --> 1:33:46.152
Those sheep won't
milk themselves.

1:33:47.022 --> 1:33:49.155
-Okay.
-No!

1:33:50.225 --> 1:33:51.358
I'll go.

1:33:55.831 --> 1:33:56.930
[DOOR OPENS]

1:34:03.705 --> 1:34:07.240
OLD JO:<i> Some things,</i>
<i> even the mountains</i>
<i> cannot solve.</i>

1:34:08.677 --> 1:34:11.645
<i> I wanted the Corporal</i>
<i> to be wrong.</i>

1:34:11.647 --> 1:34:16.182
<i> So, like Papa before me,</i>
<i> and Grandpere before him,</i>

1:34:16.184 --> 1:34:20.020
<i> I spent the summer's</i>
<i> three months in</i>
<i> the high pastures,</i>

1:34:22.290 --> 1:34:26.292
<i> alone, with just my flock</i>
<i> and my thoughts.</i>

1:34:28.030 --> 1:34:30.330
<i> My first transhumance.</i>

1:34:52.220 --> 1:34:56.723
<i> On my brief trips home,</i>
<i> all talk was about the war.</i>

1:34:56.725 --> 1:34:59.459
<i> The Americans and British</i>
<i> landing on the beaches,</i>

1:34:59.461 --> 1:35:01.928
<i> -Soviets advancing</i>
<i> from the east.</i>
-[INDISTINCT]

1:35:01.930 --> 1:35:05.799
<i> Everyone sensed that</i>
<i> it would all be over soon.</i>

1:35:05.801 --> 1:35:10.136
<i> But to me, the Germans</i>
<i> lost the war in our village</i>

1:35:10.138 --> 1:35:13.807
<i> the day they captured</i>
<i> Benjamin and Leah.</i>

1:35:13.809 --> 1:35:17.010
<i> In an instant, the uniforms</i>
<i> became the only thing</i>

1:35:17.012 --> 1:35:19.112
<i> that anyone could see.</i>

1:35:19.114 --> 1:35:21.314
<i> Their smiles were ignored,</i>

1:35:21.316 --> 1:35:24.184
<i> their small acts</i>
<i> of kindness forgotten.</i>

1:35:24.186 --> 1:35:27.153
<i> There was no hope</i>
<i> of victory after that.</i>

1:35:35.097 --> 1:35:36.496
Don't worry,
no one can see us.

1:35:39.468 --> 1:35:40.767
He gave them back?

1:35:43.872 --> 1:35:46.005
But the little cup he made me,
I shall keep forever.

1:35:48.143 --> 1:35:51.878
I will take it home when
all this is over, to remind
me of this place.

1:35:53.148 --> 1:35:54.514
Of you, of him.

1:35:56.918 --> 1:35:59.319
They were taken to one
of those camps, weren't they?

1:36:01.022 --> 1:36:03.523
-Jo, I have no answers.
-You have no answer?

1:36:03.525 --> 1:36:05.892
Or you don't want
to think about
the answer?

1:36:05.894 --> 1:36:07.527
-Jo, I...
-He was my friend.

1:36:08.230 --> 1:36:09.996
They both were.

1:36:09.998 --> 1:36:11.498
He was waiting
for his daughter,

1:36:11.500 --> 1:36:13.533
so they could escape
together to Spain.

1:36:20.008 --> 1:36:21.174
You knew, didn't you?

1:36:23.145 --> 1:36:25.245
I thought there was
someone or something

1:36:25.247 --> 1:36:26.813
you didn't want
me to see.

1:36:29.451 --> 1:36:31.184
There were seven
children in here.

1:36:32.120 --> 1:36:33.253
And they escaped.

1:36:34.556 --> 1:36:35.955
All except Leah.

1:36:41.797 --> 1:36:43.830
Well, at least we
achieved something.

1:36:52.574 --> 1:36:55.375
[DONKEY BRAYING]

1:36:56.244 --> 1:36:57.377
[DISTANT GUNFIRE]

1:37:02.050 --> 1:37:03.216
[BELLS DINGING]

1:37:06.021 --> 1:37:08.154
-[ALL CHEERING]
-[LIVELY MUSIC PLAYING]

1:37:45.126 --> 1:37:47.427
Monsieur Sarthol,
have you seen Hubert?

1:37:47.429 --> 1:37:49.262
-What is it, Jo? Huh?
-Hubert!

1:37:59.541 --> 1:38:01.041
Tell him to come
when you find him.

1:38:01.042 --> 1:38:02.542
Oh, I saw him.
He went towards
the graveyard.

1:38:25.600 --> 1:38:28.201
[HONKING]

1:38:28.203 --> 1:38:30.503
Right flank!
The boy, he has a gun!

1:38:30.505 --> 1:38:32.238
JO: [SHOUTING]
Don't, Hubert, don't!

1:38:33.408 --> 1:38:34.941
No, Hubert! No!

1:38:39.114 --> 1:38:40.980
[SOBBING]

1:38:46.521 --> 1:38:48.087
JO: Wake up! Hubert!

1:38:49.658 --> 1:38:54.294
He didn't mean it!
He didn't mean it!

1:38:55.330 --> 1:38:56.663
He didn't mean it!

1:38:56.665 --> 1:38:58.331
[SOBBING CONTINUES]

1:39:15.951 --> 1:39:18.217
[BELLS CHIMING]

1:39:19.988 --> 1:39:21.688
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

1:39:34.703 --> 1:39:36.369
[DOGS BARKING]

1:40:00.996 --> 1:40:02.195
PAPA: Jo!

1:40:02.197 --> 1:40:04.430
Ah, my love.
These are for Grandmere.

1:40:05.066 --> 1:40:06.165
Okay, Maman.

1:40:15.677 --> 1:40:19.112
HENRI: You're a star, Jo!
Put it on the table.

1:40:19.114 --> 1:40:21.414
You have some post here
as well, Madame.

1:40:21.416 --> 1:40:24.484
Will you open it for me?
And stop calling me Madame.

1:40:24.486 --> 1:40:26.486
I'm Grandmere<i> maintenant.</i>

1:40:26.488 --> 1:40:28.454
Another letter
from the mayor of Pau...

1:40:28.456 --> 1:40:30.656
Well, you can put that
in the bin.

1:40:34.195 --> 1:40:35.595
Were you expecting
a telegram?

1:40:37.499 --> 1:40:38.631
No.

1:40:40.602 --> 1:40:41.801
What does it say?

1:40:47.675 --> 1:40:48.741
"I'm on my way."

1:40:50.245 --> 1:40:51.344
ALICE: Benjamin.

1:40:52.313 --> 1:40:53.446
Anya.

1:40:56.351 --> 1:40:58.151
[EXHALES]

1:41:22.477 --> 1:41:24.577
Grandpere! Grandmere!

1:41:48.803 --> 1:41:49.869
JO: Anya!
